OpenAPI
Definition
OpenAPI is a standard specification used to describe REST APIs in a machine-readable format.
It defines:
Available endpoints
HTTP methods
Request parameters
Request body
Response body
Status codes
Authentication details
Why is OpenAPI important?
It enables tools to automatically generate:
Swagger UI
Client SDKs
API documentation
Testing tools
FastAPI automatically generates an OpenAPI specification for your application.
Flow
Python Code

↓

FastAPI

↓

OpenAPI JSON

↓

Swagger UI

↓

Interactive Documentation
Default OpenAPI URL
http://localhost:8000/openapi.json
This endpoint returns the OpenAPI specification in JSON format.
Swagger UI uses this JSON to render the documentation.
Interview Question
Q: What is OpenAPI?
Answer:
OpenAPI is a standardized specification for describing REST APIs. It allows tools to automatically generate interactive documentation, client libraries, and testing interfaces. FastAPI generates an OpenAPI specification automatically.



Why is FastAPI preferred over many traditional frameworks for API development?

A strong answer could be:
High performance due to ASGI support.
Automatic request and response validation using Python type hints.
Automatic OpenAPI specification generation.
Built-in Swagger UI and ReDoc documentation.
Excellent support for asynchronous programming.
Cleaner and more maintainable code.
